# [[encyclopedia]]

{{also|.cat|CAT|Cat|c√¢t|c√£t}}
==English==
{{wikipedia}}
[[Image:Cat03.jpg|thumb|A domestic cat]]

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|US|UK}} {{enPR|kƒÉt}}, {{IPA|en|/k√¶t/|[k ∞√¶t]|[k ∞√¶tÃö]}}
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|en|/kat/}}
* {{audio|en|En-uk-a cat.ogg|Audio (UK)}}
* {{audio|en|En-us-cat.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{audio|en|En-us-inlandnorth-cat.ogg|Audio (US-Inland North)}}
* {{rhymes|en|√¶t}}
* {{homophones|en|Kat}}

===Etymology 1===
From {{inh|en|enm|cat}}, {{m|enm|catte}}, from {{inh|en|ang|catt||male cat}}, {{m|ang|catte||female cat}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*kattuz}}.
{{rel-top|Further etymology and cognates.}}
The Germanic word is generally thought to be from {{der|en|LL.|cattus||domestic cat}} (c. 350, [[w:Rutilius Taurus Aemilianus Palladius|Palladius]]), from {{der|en|la|catta}} (c. 75 {{small|A.D.}}, [[w:Martial|Martial]]),<ref>Douglas Harper, ''Online Etymology Dictionary'', s.v. "cat", [html], retrieved on 29 September 2009: [http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=cat].</ref> from an {{der|en|afa}} language. This would roughly match how domestic cats themselves spread, as genetic studies suggest they began to spread out of the [[Near East]] / [[Fertile Crescent]] during the Neolithic (being in Cyprus by 9500 years ago,<ref name="ISample"/><ref name="COttoni"/> and Greece and Italy by 2500 years ago<ref>Dennis C. Turner, ‚ÄéPatrick Bateson, ''The Domestic Cat: The Biology of its Behaviour'' ({{ISBN|1107512212}}), page 93</ref>), especially after they became popular in Egypt.<ref name="ISample">Ian Sample, ''[https://www.theguardian.com/science/2007/jun/29/genetics.sciencenews DNA research identifies homeland of the domestic cat]'', in ''The Guardian'' (29 June 2007)</ref><ref name="COttoni">Claudio Ottoni, Wim Van Neer, Eva-Maria Geigl, et al, ''The palaeogenetics of cat dispersal in the ancient world'', in ''Nature: Ecology & Evolution'', volume 1 (19 June 2017) (doi: 10.1038/s41559-017-0139); summarized e.g. by [https://web.archive.org/web/20180516020404/http://blogs.plos.org/onscienceblogs/2017/06/23/where-did-cats-come-from/ PLOS]</ref> However, every proposed source word has presented problems. [[w:Adolphe Pictet|Adolphe Pictet]]<ref>{{R:ine:Pictet|vol=I|page=381}}</ref> and many subsequent sources refer to [[w:Barabra|Barabra]] (Nubian) {{m|onw|tr=kadd√Æska}} and "Nouba" ([[w:Nobiin language|Nobiin]]) {{m|fia|kadƒ´s}} as possible sources or cognates,<ref>Otto Keller, ''Die antike Tierwelt'', vol. 1: ''S√§ugetiere'' (Leipzig, 1909), 75; Walther von Wartburg, ed. ''[[w:Franz√∂sisches Etymologisches W√∂rterbuch|Franz√∂sisches etymologisches W√∂rterbuch]]'', vol. 2 (Basel: R. G. Zbinden, 1922‚Äì1967), 520.</ref> but M. Lionel Bender says the Nubian word is a loan from {{noncog|ar|ŸÇŸêÿ∑ŸéŸëÿ©}}.<ref name="Qitta">John Huehnergard, ‚ÄúQitta: Arabic Cats‚Äù, in ''Classical Arabic Humanities in Their Own Terms'', ed. Beatrice Gruendler (Leiden: Brill, 2008), 407‚Äì18.</ref> Jean-Paul Savignac suggests the Latin word is from an Egyptian precursor of {{cog|cop|œ£‚≤Å‚≤©||tomcat}} suffixed with feminine {{m|egy|-t}},<ref>Jean-Paul Savignac, ''Dictionnaire fran√ßais-gaulois'', s.v. "[[chat]]" (Paris: Errance, 2004), 82.</ref> but John Huehnergard says "the source [...] was clearly not Egyptian itself, where no analogous form is attested."<ref name="Qitta"/>

Huehnergard opines it is "equally likely that the forms might derive from an ancient Germanic word, imported into Latin and thence to Greek and to Syriac and Arabic". Guus Kroonen also considers the word to be native to Germanic (due to morphological alternations) and Northern Europe, and suggests that it might ultimately be borrowed from Uralic, compare {{noncog|se|gaƒëfe||female stoat}} and {{noncog|hu|h√∂lgy||stoat; lady, bride}} from {{noncog|urj-pro|*k√§ƒèw√§||female (of a fur animal)}}.<ref>{{R:gem:EDPG|*katt≈çn-}}</ref>

Related to {{cog|sco|cat}}, {{cog|fy|kat}}, {{cog|frr|k√•t}} and {{m|frr|kaat}}, {{cog|nl|kat}}, {{cog|da|kat}}, {{cog|no|katt}}, {{cog|sv|katt}}, {{cog|nds-de|Katt}} and {{m|nds-de|Katte}}, {{cog|de|Katze}}, {{cog|gsw|Chatz}}, {{cog|is|k√∂ttur}}, {{cog|af|kat}}, {{cog|la|cattus}}, {{cog|fr|chat}}, {{cog|nrf|cat}}, {{cog|oc|cat}}, {{cog|pt|gato}}, {{cog|es|gato}}, {{cog|rup|c√£tush}}, {{cog|gd|cat}}, {{cog|ga|cat}}, {{cog|br|kazh}}, {{cog|cy|cath}}, {{cog|kw|kath}}, as well as {{cog|grc|Œ∫Œ¨œÑœÑŒ±}}, {{cog|el|Œ≥Œ¨œÑŒ±}}, and from the same ultimate source {{cog|ru|–∫–æ—Ç}}, {{cog|uk|–∫—ñ—Ç}}, {{cog|be|–∫–æ—Ç}}, {{cog|pl|kot}}, {{cog|csb|k√≤t}}, {{cog|lt|katƒó}}, and more distantly {{cog|hy|’Ø’°’ø’∏÷Ç}}, {{cog|eu|katu}}, {{cog|he|◊ó◊™◊ï◊ú|tr=khat√∫l}}, {{cog|ar|ŸÇŸêÿ∑ŸéŸëÿ©}} alongside dialectal Maghrebi Arabic {{m|ar|ŸÇŸéÿ∑ŸèŸëŸàÿ≥}} (from Berber, probably from Latin).
